<ABBR>And</ABBR> also they ought not be hasty to launse <ABBR>and</ABBR> cutte apostumes <ABBR>and</ABBR> soores / ne open the heedes / ner to arrache bones broken / but yf the cause be apparant / For they myght ellys lose theyr <ABBR>good</ABBR> renome <ABBR>And</ABBR> myght better be <ABBR>callyd</ABBR> bouchers than helars or guarisshors of woun+des <ABBR>and</ABBR> soores <ABBR>And</ABBR> also hit behoueth that alle this ma|ner of peple <ABBR>foresayd</ABBR> that haue the charge for to make hole <ABBR>and</ABBR> guarisshe alle maner of maladyes <ABBR>and</ABBR> Infir|mitees that they first haue the cure of them self / <ABBR>and</ABBR> they ought to purge them self fro alle apostumes <ABBR>and</ABBR> alle vi+ces / In suche wyse that they be net <ABBR>and</ABBR> honeste <ABBR>and</ABBR> <ABBR>en|formed</ABBR> in alle <ABBR>good</ABBR> maners / <ABBR>And</ABBR> that they shewe hem hole <ABBR>and</ABBR> pure &amp; redy for to hele other <ABBR>And</ABBR> herof sayth Boecius de Consolacione In his first booke that the ster|res that ben <ABBR>hid</ABBR> vnder the clowdes maye gyue no light. <ABBR>And</ABBR> therfore yf ony man wole beholde clerly the write. Late hym wythdrawe hym fro the obscurete <ABBR>and</ABBR> der|kenes of the clowdes of ignorance / for whan the engyne of a man sheweth in Ioye or in sorowe / The pensee or thought is <ABBR>enuoluped</ABBR> in obscurete &amp; vnder the clowdes.</P>
